theorem.p:
Suppose p(x)=F(x)S(x) where the 'first' function F = F(x) and the 'second' function S = S(x) are both differentiable. Then

\begin{aligned}[t]
p'(x) \amp= F(x)S'(x)+S(x)F'(x)\\
\frac{dp}{dx}\amp= F(x)\cdot \frac{dS}{dx} + S(x) \cdot \frac{dF}{dx}
\end{aligned}

example.p:
Suppose w(x)=(x-3)(x+2). Find w'(x).
\begin{aligned}[t] w'(x) \amp= \frac{d}{dx}\left((x-3)(x+2)\right)\\ \amp= (x-3)\frac{d}{dx}(x+2) + (x+2)\frac{d}{dx}(x-3)\\ \amp= (x-3)(1) + (x+2)(1)\\ w'(x) \amp= 2x-1 \end{aligned}
Notice that we could have expanded w(x) first by multiplying the right-hand side, then taken the derivative of the result term-by-term.

theorem.p:
Suppose w(x)=\frac{T(x)}{B(x)} where the 'top' function T = T(x) and the 'bottom' function B = B(x) are both differentiable and B(x)\neq 0. Then

\begin{aligned}[t]
	w'(x) \amp= \frac{B(x)T'(x) -T(x)B'(x)}{(B(x))^2}\\
	\frac{dw}{dx} \amp= \frac{B(x)\cdot\frac{dT}{dx} -T(x)\cdot\frac{dB}{dx}}{(B(x))^2}
\end{aligned}
